The Effect of Indiaâ€™s 1996 Lok Sabha Election on Pollution Abatement and Monitoring

Michael Jerman

October 28, 2020

Introduction

  • Puzzle: India has high levels of water pollution and high abatement expenditures
  • Potential causes:
    • High marginal abatement costs
    • Marginal effects of abatement on pollution are low
    • Weak institutions/poor oversight
    • Corruption
    • Information shortages
    • Inefficient allocation of abatement infrastructure
  • This paper: Clientelism as a source of inefficient allocation of environmental resources

Summary

  • Electorally competitive cities are more likely to receive abatement funding from the federal government
  • Competitive cities are less likely to have water pollution monitoring
  • Social cost of inefficiencies are unknowable due to poor pollution monitoring

Background

  • Politics in India:
    • First-past-the-post voting
    • Castes vote monolithically (more or less)
    • Local communities benefit from same-caste leaders (state and local)
    • Many opportunities for clientelism (vote trading)

Background, Continued

  • Lok Sabha (parliament) election of 1996:
    • Highly contested, hung parliament
    • Electoral turmoil: 5 governments and 3 elections in next 5 years
    • Two main coalitions (Congress, BJP) fighting for power
    • Districts change hands frequently following 1996 election

Electoral Margin of Victory, 1996 Lok Sabha Elections

Background, Continued

  • Ganga Action Plan, Phase II (GAP II)
    • Administered by the federal government from 1996
    • $9 billion USD allocated to abatement projects along Ganges and tributaries
    • Allocation process is opaque, little oversight

Major Cities Receiving and Not Receiving GAP-II Funding

Identification

  • Main hypothesis: Policymakers disproportionately allocate environmental resources to competitive districts
  • Treatment variable: Electoral margin of victory less than 3%
    • Districts contested by main coalitions only
  • Binary outcome variables:
    • GAP II allocations to cities
    • Water quality monitoring downstream of a city after 1996
  • Identification assumption: Abatement requirements in electorally competitive districts are similar to non-competitive districts (conditional on observables)

Econometric Specification

\[Y_i = \beta D^\text{Close Election}_i + X_i \gamma + \varepsilon_i \]

  • Observations are cities \(i\) in the Ganges basin
  • \(Y_i\): Binary outcome variable (GAP II funding or water quality monitoring)
  • Control variables \(X_i\):
    • Population
    • Distance from Ganges or tributary (quadratic)
    • Nighttime light activity (level and trend)
    • Prior inclusion into federal abatement program (GAP I)
    • State and party fixed effects
  • Estimated with probit link function

Estimated Average Marginal Effect of Close Elections on Probability of Receiving GAP-II Funding:
Margin of Victory < 3%, < 5%, and < 7%

GAP II Results

  • Electorally competitive cities more likely to receive GAP II funding
  • Robustness checks:
    • Competition in 1996 does not predict prior allocations
    • Effect decreases as treatment variable becomes more inclusive
    • No effect in non-competitive cities with similar electoral compositions
    • Results robust to alternative link functions
    • Results not driven by winning-party effects

Water Quality Monitoring Stations (WQMS)

  • Sparse network of water quality monitoring stations administered by Central Pollution Control Board and Central Water Commission
  • Most cities do not have downstream monitoring stations
  • Dependent variable: WQMS opens downstream of city within three years of election
  • Downstream distance: 10km, 20km

Estimated Average Marginal Effect of Close Elections on Probability of Downstream WQMS Introduction:
Downstream Distance < 10km and < 20km

WQMS Results

  • Electorally competitive cities less likely to have pollution monitoring
  • Explanation:
    • Pollution levels are high, abatement expenditures are ineffective
    • Pollution monitoring highlights institutional failures -Robustness:
    • Electoral competition does not predict prior WQMS locations
    • Results robust to alternative link functions

Conclusion

  • Main results: Electorally competitive cities are
    • more likely to receive GAP II funding
    • less likely to have pollution monitoring
  • Social costs
    • Impossible to calculate
    • Pollution levels and abatement effects unobserved
    • Where abatement expenditures should be allocated is impossible to calculate
  • Policy implication: Drastic expansion of WQMS network
  • Research frontier: Remote sensing of water pollution levels
